efficiency: HIGH
time complexity: O(N)
space complexity: O(N)
energy implications: LOW
explanation: The solution uses a stack to keep track of prices and their corresponding spans. When a new price is encountered, it compares it to the prices in the stack. If the new price is greater than or equal to the price at the top of the stack, the span of the top price is updated, and the price is popped from the stack. This process continues until the new price is less than the price at the top of the stack. The new price is then pushed onto the stack, and its span is recorded. The algorithm has a time complexity of O(N) because, in the worst case, each price is compared to all previous prices. The space complexity is also O(N) because the stack can store up to N prices.

